This is what I have been complaining about for the past probably year and a half when it comes to "crypto-tokens"; the fundamental aspects of investment credentials do not apply as these "tokens" have been seized by same mindsets that brought you Enron and Fyre festival. Bitcoin was created as a way to utilize blockchain technology in a manner which could potentially replace FIAT transactions and was attractive to individuals as it offered the owner anonymity and security through the strength of encryption it allowed.The fact that security tokens have been turned into a commodity which people have conflated with a "store of value" calling it "digital gold" is going to be viewed through the same lenses which we look upon 1980's era "Savings and Loan Crisis" level of greed.Bitcoin has potential utility if it was used as intended, I only hope the level of greed exemplified by SBF and others doesn't ruin the concept of crypto-currency, but it certainly looks like FTX is going to be the catalyst which kicks off a Dot com era level of collapse for certain "tech companies".

There are several factors leading me to be more bearish on the dollar-denominated price of Bitcoin by November.

Increasing correlation between bitcoin prices and emerging market stocks, per IMF report. Heightened risk that this correlation could blur lines of risk between the two. Should global tensions with Russia, China negatively affect the financial environment or countries move to impose cryptocurrency restrictions, there's a chance that the overall price could fall below the threshold of $30K. Those same considerations keep me from expecting too much upward trend and so most likely outcome is that the price remains between 30-50K.

Bitcoin seems to track well with tech stocks (a generalization). The Fed will likely be more cautious about printing any new money (buying back), which will ultimately cause people to become wary of more "risky" stocks/assets, which includes Bitcoin. To reflect this, I'm pushing away from the higher end of the pricing and adding to the middle price bands.

#stochastic simulation library(dplyr) library(readr) company<-"BTC-USD" stDt <- as.Date(Sys.time()) endDt <- as.Date("2022-11-30") remainingCloses<-length(seq(stDt, endDt, "days")) forecastBands <- c(-Inf,30000,50000,70000,90000,110000,Inf) histData<-read_csv( paste0( "https://query1.finance.yahoo.com/v7/finance/download/" , company , "?period1=946684800&period2=" , floor(as.numeric(as.POSIXct(Sys.time()))) , "&interval=1d&events=history&includeAdjustedClose=true")) pricehistory<-as.numeric(histData$`Adj Close`) pricehistory<-pricehistory[!is.na(pricehistory)] spot<-pricehistory[length(pricehistory)] sdMovementRatio <- sd(log(pricehistory[1:length(pricehistory)-1]/pricehistory[2:(length(pricehistory))])) simulation<-spot*replicate(10000,cumprod(exp(rnorm(remainingCloses,mean = 0, sd = sdMovementRatio)))[remainingCloses]) cutSimulation<-as_tibble(cut(simulation,forecastBands)) mutate(count(cutSimulation,value),n/sum(n))

IMO, this question really hinges on whether the Fed can taper and not end up reversing course. Since I lean towards a failed taper and the corollary of that is additional liquidity/inflation, my long-term outlook on Bitcoin is bullish. I think eventually it'll be largely replaced by some kind of government-sanctioned stablecoin (just because the latter will be easier to use) and its price might not rise so quickly then, but unsure of timelines.

There have been three broadly steadyish states in bitcoin history, with sharp rises from one to the other, and the first two lasted for multiple years - so the best guess for the value in one year's time should be the same as the value now. But that description papers over a huge amount of noise within each state, making the specific value pretty uncertain.

I subscribe to the belief that BitCoin will eventually collapse to nothing, but that won't necessarily happen soon, and it won't necessarily be that the next major fall is final. Historically BitCoin has grown about 100x in the last 5.5 years (eyeballed), which is spectacular, and I'd be a fool to ignore the possibility that this continues and takes it well over $110K in the short term. Also historically, the price (recently $30K - $70K) has stayed relatively flat for long periods between spurts of growth and turbulence. All this leads me to a fairly wide, slightly U-shaped distribution.
The reason is because people are still into the bitcoin, the longer the people put attention into it, the more people aware of it.

I’m bearish on crypto overall right now, but I’m especially bearish on Bitcoin because it is too slow and inefficient for meaningful applications, so its price is based on pure speculation. Furthermore, it uses massive amounts of power with its proof of work consensus. I think certain coins may have long-term use (Ethereum, Solana), but I don’t see the same practical uses for Bitcoin. Yes, it was the first cryptocurrency and is still considered the main one, but other coins have popped up over the past several years that are vastly more efficient.
What is restraining crypto are regulatory and environmental issues. The evidence looks like both restraints can or will be lessened.
